r the Telugu and Tamil versions was written by Janardhana Maharshi and Crazy Mohan, respectively. The plot of the movie takes the shape of a father reading his daughter a bedtime story. Its main character Nani, who is in love with his next-door neighbor Bindu, is killed by wealthy industrialist Sudeep, who has feelings for Bindu and sees Nani as a rival. In an effort to revenge for his death and defend Bindu from the obsessive Sudeep, Nani reincarnates as a housefly. The movie's two versions, together with a Malayalam-dubbed version titled Eecha, were released on July 6, 2012, in roughly 1,100 theatres around the world. Upon its debut, the cast's performances, Rajamouli's direction, and the visual effects all won praise from critics. One of the highest-grossing Telugu movies of the year was Eega. 7. Sivaji: The Boss 2007 action movie in Tamil that was produced and directed by AVM Productions. Rajinikanth and Shriya Saran are the movie's leads, and Vivek, Suman, Manivannan, and Raghuvaran also have prominent roles. It centers around a well-established software systems architect, Sivaji, who comes home to India after ending work in the United States. He envisions returning to society and providing free medical care and educational opportunities. Adiseshan, a powerful political figure, stands in the way of his goals, though. When corruption also appears, Sivaji is forced to take on the system on his own terms. Thota Tharani served as the movie's art director, and K. V. Anand served as the film's cinematographer. A R Rahman composed the soundtrack and background music (in his 100th milestone composition). The movie, which debuted on June 15, 2007, earned favorable reviews from reviewers and went on to become a global commercial success. It then went on to win two Vijay Awards, three Filmfare Awards, and a National Film Award. The movie was made in 3D and released as Sivaji 3D on December 12, 2012. The runtime of the 3D version was shorter than the original, trimmed to 155 minutes. The movie was also the first in India to utilize Dolby Atmos surround sound. 8. Saaho Saaho was written and directed by Sujeeth in 2019 and is an Indian action thriller movie, which UV Creations made. It stars Prabhas and Shraddha Kapoor and was simultaneously shot in Hindi, Telugu, and Tamil before being dub-subtitled into Malayalam. This marks the Hindi film debuts of both Prabhas and Shraddha Kapoor as well as their respective film debuts in Telugu and Tamil. The film also stars Jackie Shroff, Arun Vijay, and Neil Nitin Mukesh in additional key roles. The film follows two covert agents who are on a quest for a crook, who has stolen ?2,000 crores (US$260 million). Soon, they understand that the case is linked to the death of a crime lord and the approaching gang war. In August 2017, Saaho's main photography commenced. India, the United Arab Emirates, Romania, and Austria were all used for filming. It is one of the most costly Indian movies ever made, with a budget of 350 crores (US$46 million). The T-Series label distributed the soundtrack for the movie. On August 30, 2019, Saaho opened in theatres and IMAX in India. The movie was the second-highest-grossing Indian movie of the year, earning over 433 crores (US$57 million) at the global box office against a budget of 350 crores (US$46 million). 9. Gabbar Singh In 2012, Harish Shankar and Bandla Ganesh released the action-comedy Gabbar Singh under Parameswara Art Productions in India. The film stars Pawan Kalyan and Shruti Haasan while Abhimanyu Singh, Ajay, Suhasini Maniratnam, Nagineedu, and Kota Srinivasa Rao play supporting roles. This Telugu remake of the 2010 Hindi film Dabangg follows the First Tamil Remake, titled Other, which was released five months earlier (in December 2011). It features STR, Richa Langella, Nassar, Nizhalgal Ravi, Sonu Sood, and other actors, with Thaman serving as the music director. The story centers on a police officer who sets out on a mission to remove a dishonest politician. The music for the movie was written by Devi Sri Prasad, and Jayanan Vincent served as the director of photography. The movie's official debut was on August 18, 2011, in Hyderabad, and it was made with a budget of 50 crore rupees ($6.6 million). Pollachi was the site of most of the filming. The film was released on 11 May 2012 and grossed over ?150 crores (US$20 million) globally, becoming one of the highest-grossing South Indian films of all time. At the 59th Filmfare Awards South, Kalyan was presented with the Filmfare Award for Best Actor - Telugu. Sardaar Gabbar Singh, the follow-up, was published in 2016. 10. Chandramukhi P. Vasu wrote and directed the 2005 Tamil-language comedy-horror movie. The movie stars Rajinikanth, Prabhu, Jyothika, Vadivelu, and Nayanthara and is a remake of Vasu's Kannada film Apthamitra (2004), which was itself a remake of the Malayalam film Manichitrathazhu (1993). Nassar, Sheela, Vijayakumar, Vinaya Prasad, Sonu Sood, Suvarna Mathew, and Vineeth also acted in the movie. The story centers on a woman who has a family-wide dissociative identity disorder and a psychiatrist who wants to solve the case at any cost. Chandramukhi is the 50th movie that Prabhu and his brother Ramkumar Ganesan have produced via Sivaji Productions. Vidyasagar wrote the background music and soundtrack CD. Sekhar V. Joseph handled the filming, and Suresh Urs handled the editing. On October 24, 2004, the first day of principal photography, it ended in March 2005. A 119-crore budget was used to produce the movie. On the eve of the Tamil New Year, on April 14, 2005, Chandramukhi was made public. With an 890-day theatrical run at Shanti Theatre, the movie was a huge financial hit. The movie received two Filmfare Awards, four Film Fans' Association Awards, and five Tamil Nadu State Film Awards. For their contributions to the movie, Jyothika and Vadivelu were both given a Kalaimamani Award. In Telugu, a stand-alone prequel called Nagavalli (2010) was produced. Ne